 countries from Australia to the United States, Canada, and Europe; –visual art, including oil paintings by Theanly Chov and excerpts from a graphic novel by Tian Veasna.“The work included in Out of the Shadows of Angkor is just a part of the vast, diverse repertoire of Cambodian literature created by those born in Cambodia, in the camps, and in new lands. Soth Polin once told me, ‘What we have lost is indescribable . . . what we have lost is not reconstructable. An epoch is finished. So when we have literature again, it will be a new literature.’ We hope this book brings out of the shadows some of the lost, hidden, and emerging gems of Cambodian literature—past, present, and moving into the future.” —From the overview essay by guest editor Sharon May  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aMacquet, Christophe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMay, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMay, Sharon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRatner, Vaddey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSo, Phina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStewart, Frank, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSvay, Sokunthary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaing, Rinith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWalker, Trent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Trent, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978082489454240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082489684340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824896843423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824896843/original  aEBA_CL_LT 